    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-05-09T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-05-09T12:00:00-05:00" n="37"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d37">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">320/5–950: telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Douglas</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-05-09T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 9, 1950—6 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2527. Parrott<note n="1" xml:id="d37fn1">Cecil C. Parrott, head of the United
                        Nations (Political) Department, British Foreign Office.</note> indicated
                    Foreign Office has learned unofficially through Hector McNeil<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d37fn2">British Minister of State (Foreign Office), member of the
                        British Delegation to the fourth and earlier regular sessions of the General
                        Assembly.</note> that Zafrullah Khan<note n="3" xml:id="d37fn3">Sir Muhammad
                        Zafrullah Khan, Pakistani Minister of Foreign Affairs and Commonwealth
                        Relations.</note> intends to stand as <pb facs="0109" n="93" xml:id="pg_93"
                    /> President Fifth <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss>. UK feels obligated to vote
                    for Zafrullah as he had been UK candidate for President Fourth <gloss
                        target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> and stood down for Romulo.</p>
                <p>Parrott also stated that as Pakistan has felt badly treated in <gloss
                        target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> election, Zafrullah would be a good thing. He
                    added both Zafrullah and Entezam regarded as excellent candidates but that UK
                    would feel bound to vote for Zafrullah in light of previous events.</p>
                <p>Foreign Office would be interested in Department’s latest thinking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Douglas</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
